-\nB\neautiful\neecftwood\nH1BLER AND RUSSELL\nLESSEES AND MANAGERS.\nT. NEAI, IICIIHAKD,\nMaslcnl Director.\nfirst Clearance Sale\nOf\nSummer Goods!\nBegins at tfte Ilew VorR Store\nOursday, jjune 25tft!\nCo be (Mimed ilNtil\nSaturday, 3uty 4tl).\nParticulars Cater.\nNew York Store.\nS. STRAUS, Proprietor.\nI\nMAIL.\n75\n.JIS Cent\n0 JfontA.\ni\nIN ADVANCE.\nRemarkable Slump\nin Immigration.\nplEq\nisi\nh\ncracifacTratnrgtMt7ggacn7grr3eTtKicrgcCTRiKiatc\nTWINE\nFOR\nSALE\nBY\n7jn entire cbange of\nJ program at Beecfr\nwood toniflM Be\nsure and go out you will\nenjoy it\nCharley Fairbanks wasbuiltQ run but he\ncouldn't go even a little bit. t x\nr\nSometimes the bursting qf a littlo Bant\nmakes more noise than tho bursting of a big\nBank. Tho Aberdeen Bank failure shows\nwhat a small fry institution can do when it\ngoes into the busting business.\nIn the month of May only 42,000 immi\ngrants landed in this country; 75,000 aliens\nsailed for their old homes. For the same\nmonth last year the\narrivals were 198,000\nand thedepartureswere\n33,000.\nSince last October,\nwhen the panic took\neffect, 550,000 aliens havo left these shores and\nonly about 150,000 have arrived.\nThe departure of so great an army of un\nskilled labor served to reduce materially the\nhard-times conditions of many localities. The\nhalf million would have been added to the un\nemployed, and this would have meant for most\nof them an eventual approach to destitution.\nThe steamship companies expect the steerage\ntraffic to continue in its present swing for some\ntime. When the return of prosperity is as\nsured it should show the old balance the other\nway.\nNever in previous history has the automatic\nregulation of immigration and emigration been\nso strikingly exhibited as by the port figures\nfor the last eight months. New York World.\nlr,iOPCiCCCmICICtlOTITOIIII!or3p1\n3\n3\nBROUGHT TO BOOK.\n\"Sir,\" says the aggrieved customer, approaching the\nbookseller, \"I have called to express my opinion of your\nbusiness methods!\"\n''What is wrong?\" deferentially asked the bookseller.\n\"I bought a set of Shakespeare from you last year. It\nweighed fourteen pounds. Yesterday I ordered a dupli\ncate set for my son's library, and it only weighs thirteen\npounds and nine ounces. I'd have you understand, sir,\nthat there is a city ordinance against short weights.\"\nThoroughly humbled, the bookseller made up the\nshortage with seven ounces of miscellany.\nMm. Edward Elston of Bellevue and Mrs. E.\nS. Edgington, Mra. R. H. Pollitt and J. S. Ede\nington of Covington were called here by the\ndeath of Mr. James Evans.\nMiss Gartmell's School!\nMist Cartmcll's will open her School to: Girls\nnd Hoys nt tlie Couveru, Hast Third street, Sep\ntember 7th, IPCS, und will tench from first crude\nto High School. For particulars see or write\nMISS CARTMKLL,\nJe52 eod2m At 30 West Frout Street.\nNOTICE\nWe will cut to order and deliver oak lumber,\nany size and dimension and lencth, to any place\nIn Fleming or Masoncountles. For further partic\nulars call on O. II. P. Thomas A Co., or address II.\nv. inomas, it. p. u. .no. 3, Maysvllle, K\nouiMi uius a specialty.\ne231ra\nSCHOOL BUILDING FOR SALE\nBy order of tho Board of Education, the\nold First Ward School Building, corner Third\nand Short streetB, will be offered at public\nsale at 2 p. m. Monday, June 29th, 1908.\nPKorEitTY Committee.\nM. F. COUGHLIN GO.\nFOR FINE LIVERY TURNOUTS\nUNDERTAKING\nAND EMBALMING.\nRuggles\nCamp Meeting\nJjily 23 to Aug. 2, 1908.\nOne of our Hlihops will doubtless be present on\nthe first Sunday.\nDr. II. C. Jamison, Presiding Elder of the Cin\ncinnati District, Cincinnati Conference, will be\npresent and preach on tho second Sunday, The\nsinging will be In charge of a special long evan\ngelist. During the meeting the Ministers of tho\nKentucky Conference will be heard.\nTHE PRIVILEGES WILL BE LET\nJULY 4th\nAt the Old Settlers' Plcnlo on the ground. He\nsure to attend me uia seiners' j'icnio'July 1th.\ndin. Round trie from MivstIIIo Ihn. iimki\nTwo-story oottagei 17; one-alorv 5 for the ten\ntui\nmeet morning ana evening train., for informa\nr\ntion conceding cottages, room., eta,,\nottajtes, room., eto., ftppljr tolflflfY\nn'hAVJl, May.nilet'J\",'\nlatest 3tcw-s\nli. G. Dun. Co announce'\nthat the outlook for fall trade\nis very encouraging.\nTho Iron and Steel Trade\nJournal of London maintains\ninternational steel combination\nis being formed.\nHenry M. Flagler has re\nsigned as Vice-President of the\nStandard Oil Company, and is\nsucceeded by W. H. Tilford.\n\nThe Postoffice Department\nhas issued a fraud order against\nseveral Cleveland firms for using\nthe mails for fraudulent pur\nposes. The locust pest has made its\nappearance in Karnes county,\nTexas, and already hundreds of\nacres of cotton and corn have\nbeen destroyed.\nThe President and Mrs.\nRoosevelt and children left\nWashington Saturday morning\nfor Oyster Bay to spend the\nsummer months.\nThere is no trouble in the\nPhilippines, and the report that\nthe first Assembly made any\ndemand fo independence is de\nnied by Governor-General\nSmith.\nTaftand Sherman held a con\nference at Cincinnati Saturday.\nThe matter of selecting the\nChairman of the National Com\nmittee wa3 deferred for two\nweeks.\nIn the case of the Common\nwealth against the American\nTobacco Company, in the An\nderson Circuit Court at Law\nrenceburg, the Jury imposed a\nfine of $1,000 for violation of\nthe Anti-Trust Law.\nMadrid, June 20th. Two\nhundred and fifty people were\nkilled in the Megadouro Dis\ntrict of Portugal and 150 sailors\nand fishermen were drowned on\nthe Portugese and Spanish\ncoasts by severe storms.\nAt Louisville, W. N. Harts\nhorn of Boston, the recognized\nleader of the Sunday-school\nforces of America, was re-elected\nChairman of the Executive\nCommittee of the International\nSunday-school Association.\nWesloy Sutherland, a farmer\nof Boyle county, was killed\nwhile riding a mule. Tho mule\nthrew him, and Sutherland, in\nfalling, becamo entangled in the\nharness. The mule dragged\nand kicked him around a hundred-acre\nfield, crushing his\nskull and mangling his body.\nIt will be learned with pain\nand regret by the many friends\nand admirers of the late Gen\neral Benjamin Rush Cowen that\na largo shortage has been found\nin his accounts as Clerk of tho\nUnited States Circuit and Dis\ntrict Courts for tho Southern\nDistrict of Ohio at Cincinnati.\nIt will amount to at least $25s\nrU.\n1Wi i K.i. K y,. 'I.TIH\nLondon was:attended by 500,\n000 people.\"\n'Reports are current that 74\npersons were killed by a torna\ndo at Albert-Lea, JVIinn.\nSecretary Taft's train en\nroute to Washipgton narrowly\nescaped wrecking at Coshocton,\nO., yesterday.\ni.., i\nThe State of Kentucky has\nexpended $40,000 in trying to\nend the tobacdo troubles. Ohio\nhas spent $45,000.\nIn an opinion by Judge Las\nsing, the Court of Appeals holds\nthat some 300,000 acre's of land\nin Pike, Leslie, Perry and other\nmountain counties are forfeited\nto tho Commonwealth for fail\nure to list for taxation.\nSecretary Taft was given a\ngreat ovation on his arrival at\nCincinnati Saturday morning.\nHe went into Cincinnati over\nthe B. and O. S.-W. instead of\nthe C. and O., and thus several\nhundred persons who had gath\nered at the Depot here were dis\nappointed at not seeing the Re\npublican nominee for President.\nTROOPS AT MAYSVILLE\nCompany C of Second Regi\nment Here The Bracken\nCounty Trouble Not\nOver\nTwo officers and twenty men\nof Company C, Second Rogi\nmentjKeutuckyNationalGuards, left Lexington this morning\nover the Chesapeake and .Ohio\nRailroad at 5 o'clock f orBracken\ncounty, where it is probables\nthey will remain for the rest of\nthe summer.\nCaptain R. V. Jones received\na telephone message from the\nAdjutant General's office in\nFrankfort yesterday afternoon\nat 1 o'clock telling him to de\ntail the Company and take the\nmen to Maysville this morning\nby train.\nAt Maysville the Company\nwill be mounted and proceed\nin the saddle across country to\nBrooksville, tho county seat of\nBracken county, from which\ncanip Company C returned last\nweek after a six weeks' service.\nDETAIL WILL JOIN THEM.\nAt Brooksville Company C\nwill be joined 'by a detail of\nfifteen men from tho unassigned\nInfantry Company from Beatty\nvillo. Tho camp, will be lo\ncated probably at tho farm of\nGeorge Kinney, about one milo\nbeyond Brooksville.\nThe men do riot know how\nlong they will be gone, but\nthey are prepared to stay\nsummer.\nall\nCaptain Casey has contracted\nwith Coughlin Co. of this\ncity for the uso of twenty head\nof horses for tho soldiers\nnow. in tho field in Bracken\n;cpnrity for the next ninety days,\nTlie Buffragetto meeting in\n'!i uiii: unt. um.ii MMtV,g',H?!gR\nIrak singing!\nBULB I :X\nJ Br A. H. MARTIN\n\n\"I noticed It Drat about a week ago,,\nJuBt after I had returned from a visit\nto the club. I had Btarted to read for\na halfhour before retiring. The vol\nume contained several fantastic\nstories, including the 'Masque of the\nRed Death.' Suddenly I became\nnwaro of a sound as If some one was.\nsinging, and the singer seemed to bo\nIn tho room. It was a sad melody,,\nas I remember, and the voice was\nwonderfully sweet and gentle. It was\na woman's voice, and it was reproach\ning me because I had so soon forgot\nten her.\n\"And you know, Frank, tjiat It was'\nonly a JiVir ago that Hilda died. It.'\nwas suddenly borne upon me that I\nwas listening to Hilda's voice singing\nto me from another world. Un to,'\nthat time I felt no alarm, but now l'\nfelt my hair commence to rise. All\n.u\nat once my gazo becamo riveted on.\ntho single electric hulb that Illu\nminated tho apartment. Frank, as\nsure as I am a living man, tho voice\nproceeded from that lamp. And since\nthen it has happened regularly every\nnight, until I believe that I will go\ninsane unless tho mystery is solved.'\"\n\"Undoubtedly the mystery has a hu\nman origin,\" I replied, as I regarded\nmy cigar reilectively, \"although I\nmust say that it is certainly an orig\ninal way to Impersonate the departed.\nIs there anyone whoNvould bo bene\nflted by your death or incarceration,\neven temporarily, in an Insane ward?\"\"\n\"The only one who could be in any\nway benefited 1b Edward Duval, Hil\nda's only brother.\"\nDuring tho day I did o little quiet,\ndetective work, and discovered things\nrelating to Edward Duval that did not\nspeak very favorably for him. At the\npresent time he was Infatuated with\nFanny Davidson, a burlesque actressy\n1 made my way to John's house,,\nand we were soon seated in the\nlibrary discussing the strange affair\nin lowered tones. The Bemidarkness\ncast by the solitary lamp, and Uie pe\nculiar mission thnt had brought me\nthero had a depressing effect upon us.\nSuddenly a woman's voice one of the\nsweetest and saddest I have ever\nheard Issued from tho glowing bulb\nand pervaded tho entire apartment.\nThe song was a sentimental one and\nreproached another for.tho cooling or\nhis love.\nForcing down a sensation of hor\nror, I removed the globe from tho\nsocket. Tho song instantly ceased.\nIn a moment I had screwed in an\nother globe that I had brought with\nme. Instantly the song was renewed\nwith all its original power and sweet\nness. John had sunk bock in his\nchair. Even my nerves were shaken.\nSuddenly tho voice ceased, only to\nbegin again. And It called John by;\nname to the unknown, and it prom\nised the delights of paradise if he\nheeded the call.\nWith a wild cry John sprang to his\nfeet and dashed to tho' door. His wild\nshriek aroused me, and suddenly a\nlight broko over me. With one\nspring I had reached John, and after\na desperate struggle forced him Into\na chair.\n\"The mystery Is one no longer,\" I\ncried, as I held him down.\n\"What are you gplng to do about\nIt?\" and Edward Duval snarled up at\nme, as I confronted him in his apart\nments. \"I will give you five hours to leave\nChicngo, never to return,\" I replied\nas quietly as I could. \"Doth you and\nyour accomplice.\"\n\"Before I leave do you mind telling\nme now you came to detect tho con\ntrivance?\" asked Duval, after a mo\nment's moody silence.\n\"Had you been content with iho ex\ncellent song, I might still have been\nat sea,\" said I, \"but the Instant you\ncommenced your other tactics, tho\ntruth flashed upon mo. I hurried to\nFanny Davidson's apartments. A\ntelephone wire ran from tho build\ning to John's house. Directly I be\ncame nwaro that tho samo voice I\nhad heard In the library was proceed\ning from her rooms.\n\"Cautiously glancing inside, I ob\nserved that a flno phonograph was\nconnected with tho transmitter of tho\nopen telephone. Then I observed\nthat tho telephone wire was connect\ned with the electric lino In such a\nway that when the bulb in the library\nwas open tho voice from the phono\ngraph was forced to issue from tho\nlighted globe. If the globe was re\nmoved the voice would, of course,\ncease as soon as the circuit was\nbroken.\"\nWith- a snarl Duval commenced\npacking his trunk.\nLondon's Electric Railways.\nIt is stated that on tho three tubo\nrailways, comprising 41.C8 miles of\nsinglo lino, controlled by tho Under\nground Electric Railways Company of\nLondon, tho number of automatic slg\nnals averages 15.85 per milo, and that\nthose signals drop and riso 1,6:18,282\ntimos week. Tho (weekly coBt of\nmaintenance is said to bo 4 3s. 6 C8d.\nper track mile, 5s. 3 22d. per signal,\nand 0 457d- ner train milo.\nJpecial Request.\nWTn antecrtngadverHements apptaiinginth\ncolumn, of Vtli naptr, or whm luvlng poo from a\nmcrchanticho$iintvertticmcitipptariinthtipittr.\ntau the aJytrtUttopU n The Jni?uu IiKpOBnUf. qPK\nttf)rWnM hu'StK MA aihrtlir ttni Iht HdUtiffim&r\n4i wm rw vuh nuwiJ7, unu w uu vp KrwcuiufHH,\n',i\nV\nH-\n\n\n3B. 1 t\nU.I, .j it h i i 1 i, u. i i I\nIftHMBtJaBgBMalBltlB\n\"\"\"\"\"Sfflf","height":"28312","width":"19908"}}
